Looks like we found the Y offset.  I get those values by transforming (0,0,0) in the head frame to the world frame using a transform listener (listen_).
It is almost the first step in the entire program.
Here is the code (in the actual code, this is wrapped in a try/catch), assuming that the transform listener has been initialized and passed as listener_

```
#!python

geometry_msgs::PointStamped zeroPointWorldFrame, zeroPointHeadFrame_;
	zeroPointHeadFrame_.point.x = 0.0;
	zeroPointHeadFrame_.point.y = 0.0;
	zeroPointHeadFrame_.point.z = 0.0;
	zeroPointHeadFrame_.header.frame_id = "head";
	zeroPointHeadFrame_.header.stamp = ros::Time();
listener_.transformPoint("world", zeroPointHeadFrame_, zeroPointWorldFrame);
```
